# basic_example.rlx
# Demonstrates the two fundamental rule types:
#   1. An unconditional rule that always fires.
#   2. A conditional rule that fires based on current state.

# Rule 1: always fires, sets x to 1.
=> x = 1

# Rule 2: fires only when x equals 1, then sets y to 2.
# Because rule 1 ran first (pipeline model), x is already 1 by the time
# this condition is checked.
x == 1 => y = 2
